    This course will offer a unique investors point of view of Emerging Markets emphasizing different characteristics of frontier, emerging and developed country indices. Analyzing asset allocation decisions within Emerging Market countries will be a key theme of this course. Economic theory and accompanying evidence will be extensively employed to identify and explain sources of relative returns between Emerging Market countries. Relative performance trends within a country, at sector or individual stock level, will also be discussed in detail. Investment vehicles available to today&rsquo;s global investors will be presented with real live examples including ETFs, Closed End Funds, ADRs or investments in locally listed stocks/bond and OTC derivative instruments. 
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Limits to market efficiency, restrictive or unpredictable regulatory frameworks, transaction costs and ownership limitations still create headwinds to investors in emerging markets, but improvements in fiscal &amp; monetary policies and relative political stability offer unique investment opportunities for the next decade or the next century for some strong believers of Emerging Markets story. While keeping the main focus on rationale of portfolio investments in emerging markets, the course will also cover theoretical foundations of economic growth, business cycles, and economic policy in Emerging Market economies. 
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Recommended to: Public officers covering international markets (Treasury, FED, State Department etc..), Consultants, Country Analysts, Portfolio Managers, Traders, Asset Allocators and to anyone who is interested in international finance with Emerging Markets focus.
 &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Course Organization 	
Each participant of the course will be assigned to one emerging market country as a Country Analyst. Country Analysts are responsible to closely follow macroeconomic, political and major market driven events of the country they are covering. Active participation in information sharing between country analysts via group e-mails is required during the course of this class. At the end of the semester, analysts are expected to be able to explain sources of relative performance of the country they covered and also show ability to provide actionable investment ideas utilizing theoretical and practical tools they acquired during the semester.

    Let&rsquo;s hope they don&rsquo;t discover oil here. Then we&rsquo;d have real problems.&rdquo; So says a stunned survivor from a destroyed village in the movie Blood Diamond. Natural resources have been at the root of human conflict for millennia, and for much of that time, the main response to resources-driven conflict was more conflict. Like the villagers in the movie, many have come to view the discovery and exploitation of natural resources as a curse that ultimately leads to corruption, bloodshed, and environmental degradation.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
In recent decades, however, the United States, the broader international community, and the private sector have developed a range of legal, policy, and regulatory approaches to curb resource-focused conflict and corruption, seeking to turn the curses into blessings. These range from certification systems (such as the Kimberley Process for conflict diamonds), reporting mechanisms (Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative), due diligence standards (OECD Due Diligence Guidance), industry standards (Responsible Jewelry Council) and economic sanctions (import prohibitions and specific, targeted sanctions). In this course, we will examine these recent approaches through specific case studies and interrogate whether they can &quot;work&quot; through the lenses of governments (both Western and non-Western), industry, civil society, and local communities.

    From RAND&#39;s nuclear wargames underpinning Mutually Assured Destruction (MAD), to the Naval War College exercises preparing the Allies for WW2, gaming has a storied history as a tool of military planning and strategic decision-making. Also sometimes called &ldquo;Serious Gaming&rdquo; or &ldquo;Strategic Gaming,&rdquo; Wargaming has evolved from its origins as a Prussian tool of military education to a multi-faceted field exploring Climate Change adaptation, IUU Fishing, Artificial Intelligence competition, international migration, and much more in addition to its traditional use in National Security contexts. With rising uncertainty and rapid technological progress around the world, both civilian and military continue to turn to Wargaming to inform decision-making across the US Government.
&lt; br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This course aims to both equip students to understand the abilities and limitations of wargaming and prepare them to design professional games themselves on a topic of their choosing. Covering the philosophy and practice of designing professional wargames for policy or military audiences, the course will lead students through taking a game from a sponsor request to a functional prototype. In-class lectures and facilitation of different professional and commercial games will prepare students for the semester-long project of designing a playable wargaming prototype.

    Illicit Finance: Impacts on corruption, national security, and development
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The IMF estimates that money laundering comprises roughly 2 to 5 percent of the world&rsquo;s GDP each year ($1.74 trillion to $4.35 trillion). Much of this illicit money originates in the developing world and finds a convenient hiding place in the financial centers of the developed world. The negative impacts of illicit financial flows (IFFs) strike not only at the heart of a country&rsquo;s economy but also increase the threats of instability, violence, and political and human insecurity, for not just the country in question but also for other countries in the region.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This course will focus on developing an understanding of IFFs as a many-faceted problem with countries both rich and poor culpable in different ways. To delve into this problem, the course will utilize real-world case examples to understand the complementary roles that source, transit, and destination countries play. More specifically, the course will help students think critically about industries that act as easy sources of illicit capital, legal environments that protect individual property rights without asking probing questions about the sources of wealth, the methods to move these ill-gotten gains, and ongoing US policy mechanisms to highlight the full scope of this issue.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This course straddles the study of law, economics, political science, and human rights.

    Debt and Development: The Promise, Perils, Policies, and Practices of a Double-Edged Instrument
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This course provides an &ldquo;advanced introduction&rdquo; to debt policy and debt management in developing countries. While the main focus will be on public debt, it will also explain the implications of borrowing by sub-nationals, corporations, and households. The approach will be comprehensive&mdash;conceptually, institutionally, geographically, and thematically. The idea is to help students understand how debt works; who borrows and who lends and why; what various good and bad country experiences have taught us; and what the current and forthcoming policy issues around debt financing are. So coverage will span from the macroeconomic drivers of debt and the ways to know whether debt is sustainable, down to the legal and institutional underpinnings of public borrowing. We will delve into evolving issues like debt defaults and debt relief, contingent liabilities, and lending for infrastructure. And we will explain the new generation of financing instruments, notably thematic bonds (green, blue, gender, SDG, sukuk, etc.) and fiscal insurance (against, say, natural disasters and commodity price volatility).

    What is strategy and what are some of the main concepts, tools and techniques to assist in strategic analysis? What are the relationships between strategy and financial statements? Does strategy drive the numbers or do numbers drive the strategy? Finally, how does the integration of strategy and finance generate value and how might we try to measure this?
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The course is split into 4 sections:
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
o Strategy &ndash; an introduction to strategy with case led application
o Finance - a case led refresher of key financial tools and metrics including financial modelling
o Valuation &ndash; an introduction to valuation
o Case led integration of the above
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Using a mix of theory, news events, blogs and research reports the course will draw upon current events to illustrate and analyze key principles.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Learning Objectives &amp; Pedagogy
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The key learning objective is for participants to gain the theoretical and practical expertise necessary to understand, analyze and debate the relationships between strategy, finance and value. In particular, the end-game is to be able to integrate the three &ldquo;knowledge silos&rdquo; of strategy, finance and valuation.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Class discussion and homework assignments, both individual and team based, will grow the ability to analyze and fluently present insightful integration of the above.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Whilst MSFS 515 is not a pre-requisite some base level of financial knowledge is required. Those who have not taken a finance course must read Financial Intelligence &ndash; &ldquo;A Managers Guide to Knowing what the Numbers Really Mean&rdquo; in advance of starting the course.

    Course Title: Tech4Development: Applying Technology to Sustainability Challenges
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Context: This class combines two of the most significant and transformational themes of our time: exponential technological advancement and global sustainability. Technology is disrupting every component of our lives: every business, every government, every investor. Environmental Social and Governance (ESG) issues, and broad-based Sustainability challenges are now being discussed at the highest level - from the cabinet table to the boardroom. Consumers, citizens, and investors alike are increasingly demanding &ldquo;sustainable&rdquo; behavior in ways the world has never seen. Regardless of the direction of your life and career aspirations, these two horizontal themes will disrupt your world and our planet.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) - from water and health to the environment and education - are bold in their ambition, sweeping in their breadth and gargantuan in their price tag. The only chance the world has of achieving the sustainability targets imbedded in the SDGs will be to aggressively apply technological solutions to solve problems. Technological advancements such as AI, blockchain, biometrics, API, AR-VR, alternative payment models, micro-grids and advances in connectivity, including 5G) represent an extraordinary tool kit, exponentially more powerful when combined. This promise will only be realized if technology is applied and deployed against the world&rsquo;s sustainability challenges; success will come by piloting, funding and scaling these solutions, and from businesses implementing &ldquo;do-good, do-well&rdquo; models.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Course Description: The first phase of the course will help you develop a foundational knowledge of critical and emerging technologies. If you are new to tech, this course will leap you forward into the disrupted digital world. If you are well versed in tech, this course will help push you deeper into their applications and inter-related tech solutions. Either way you will leave the course with a comprehensive tech vocabulary, and enough knowledge to conceptually apply solutions.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The second phase of the course will explore concrete ways that technology can be applied to sustainability challenges. We will look at real-life applications, with a special focus on private sector , tech-driven solutions.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Finally, the course will examine how developmental entities and NGOs are grappling with deploying new technological solutions and recipes for success.
Approach and Methodology: The syllabus is online. Students will be given core reading on transformational technologies and tested on each. Class lectures and discussion will be re-enforced with video content and special guests from the private-tech sector and from the policy developmental community (quizzes and participation will be part of the grade). At the beginning of the course, each student will select one SDG and conduct research on how technologies can be applied to achieve it. This project will culminate in a paper/memo and a presentation to the class. The work of A students will be given to leaders in the development community.

    &quot;Branding is a key driver of customer demand, enabling organizations to command significant price premiums over competitors. Thus, brand equity is of vast commercial worth and its creation, development, and leverage are a critical component of effective marketing. This course is designed to develop your understanding of how to build, measure and manage brand equity. ns, and will stress the critical roles of both creativity and managerial intuition as well as data and analysis.

The main learning objectives of this course are:
- To understand the relevant theories and models to make effective branding decisions;
- To develop the skills to design and implement brand programs, such as:
  - Creating compelling positioning statements;
  - Understanding how to reverse engineer brand positioning strategies;
  - Planning a brand activation program to convert strategy into action;
  - Measuring and evaluating brand performance.
- To strengthen the ability to critically assess competitive positions and gain an appreciation for the difficulty and ambiguity associated with developing and leading a brand at the mid to senior levels of an organization.&quot;

